A-Assertions: Add assert statements to enforce invariants

A-Assertions: Add assert statements to enforce invariants > > TaskList and Ui classes have important assumptions that must hold > for the program to work correctly. For example: > - Index used in getTask(int) and deleteTask(int) must be within range > - Tasks added or retrieved must not be null > - Search strings in findTasks(String) must not be null > > Adding assert statements helps: > * Document these assumptions clearly in code > * Catch violations early during development/testing > * Improve code reliability and maintainability > > Let's insert assert statements in: > - TaskList.getTask(int), deleteTask(int), findTasks(String) > - Ui.showTaskList(TaskList), Ui.showTaskAdd(Task)

A-Streams: Refactor loops to use Java Streams > > Several loops in TaskList and Ui classes can be expressed more > cleanly using Java Streams and functional programming constructs. > > Changes include: > * TaskList.findTasks(String) uses Arrays.stream + filter + toArray > * Ui.showTaskList(TaskList) and Ui.showFindingTasks(TaskList) use >   IntStream.range + mapToObj + forEach > > Benefits of this refactor: > * Code is more concise and readable > * Emphasizes functional programming style > * Makes future maintenance and updates easier > > Let's adopt streams in these places to modernize the code while > preserving all existing functionality.
A-Streams: Refactor findTasks to use Streams
commitResults.messageBody:
Previously, findTasks used a for-loop to collect matching tasks, which was
verbose and imperative. By using Arrays.stream() + filter() + toArray(),
the logic becomes more declarative and easier to read.

Changes:
- Replaced for-loop with Arrays.stream().filter().toArray()
- Ensures functionality remains unchanged
- Improves readability and maintainability

commitResults.messageTitle: A-CodeQuality: Refactor Parser and Task for readability and maintainability
commitResults.messageBody:
The Parser class previously had inconsistent switch-case formatting, which
made reading and extending the code harder. The Task class also had
unclear function names that reduced clarity.

Improvements:
- Reformatted switch-case statements in Parser to standard style
- Renamed Task functions to better describe their behavior
- Ensures code style consistency across classes
- Makes future maintenance and feature extension easier

These changes improve code readability, maintainability, and align with
project coding standards without altering existing functionality.

Refactor Storage to follow SLAP and improve code quality
commitResults.messageBody:
The Storage class previously handled low-level file I/O and high-level
data parsing within the same methods. This mixed levels of abstraction
made the code harder to maintain.

This commit refactors Storage by:
* Extracting directory and file preparation into prepareFile().
* Abstracting task parsing logic into parseTaskFromStorage().
* Replacing magic strings with private static constants.
* Adding Java assertions to document internal assumptions about
  file paths and task arrays.

These changes improve readability and ensure the class adheres to the
Single Level of Abstraction Principle (SLAP).
